elements.content: Three supramolecular networks are synthesized by the combination of Mn(II) and flexible ligands [1,2-bis (4-pyridyl) ethane (bpe); 1,3-bis (4-pyridyl) propane (bpp); 4,4‘-bipyridyl disulfide (bpds)], characterized by single-crystal X-ray analysis. All three complexes have extended solid-state structure formed by π−π interactions, and there is an excellent opportunity to elucidate the difference in the formation of extended networks in these three complexes. Complex 1, which is reported in a paper earlier by our group, is an unprecedented three-dimensional (3D) “honeycomb”-like architecture constructed from a novel sinusoidal one-dimensional (1D) chain [Mn(bpe)(H2O)4]2+ through π−π interactions in which bpe is used as a bidentate bridging ligand. Complex [{Mn(bpp)3Cl2}(H2O)2] n 2 generates a “standing wave”-like architecture by π−π interactions from a neutral zigzag 1D chain of [Mn(bpp)3Cl2]. Complex [{Mn(bpds)2(dca)2(H2O)2}(H2O)4(bpds)] n 3 is a neutral monomer [Mn(bpds)2(dca)2(H2O)2], which is self-assembled to form a two-dimensional sheet by hydrogen bonding. These sheets interact to generate 3D supramolecular structure stabilized by an interesting “sandwiched” π-interaction involving both coordinated and solvated bpds. Solid-state fluorescence results of these flexible ligands and complexes are in agreement with their structures.

Introduction

One of the major goals of crystal engineering is targeted at the predictable assembly of molecular species into extended architectures. Presently, inorganic crystal engineering is focused on the functionalization of material in the solid state. But the most intriguing aspect of the latter is the notion of one day being able to manipulate not only the features of specific molecules, but also the bulk, intermolecular characteristics, and properties of the entire crystalline aggregate. Therefore, one of the most necessary tasks of current research is the fabrication of supramolecular self-assembly organized by covalent or noncovalent interaction, as they have a variety of potential applications such as host-guest chemistry, and molecular/optoelectronic devices. Among weak noncovalent forces, hydrogen bonds are commonly used as "structure directing" and hence allow speculating on their application on crystal design. In contrast, to date little attention has been paid by inorganic coordination chemists to π-π interactions for tuning the topology and for establishing crystal structures. However, this interaction can contribute up to 10 kJ mol-1 as intermolecular attractive energy through the well-known face-to-face and C-H⋅⋅⋅π/edge-to-face interactions. The key factor, to design a solid-state architecture tuned by π-π interactions between the low-dimensional (1D or 2D) polymeric networks, is the proper choice of ligands. Although the utilization of cooperative, weaker π-interactions have proved a powerful tool for linking organic molecules into crystal-engineered structures, their combination with polypyridyl metal complexes has received scant attention. We have already communicated the importance of involving such additional interactions in the formation of porous three-dimensional (3D) coordination polymeric networks of the complex. Combinations of such noncovalent interactions in the formation of a 3D porous network are also documented. Crystal engineering on ruthenium(II) and platinum(II) terpyridyl complexes involving π-stacking interactions increased extinction coefficients and extended emission lifetimes. Thus, π-stacking noncovalent interactions might offer an alternative means of controlling the assembly of photoactive metal centers as well as the formation of 3D coordination polymer networks containing channels.

elements.content: Hence, to investigate the effect of π-stacking interactions on an assembly, our design strategy was to create different electronic environments on the pyridyl rings changing the linker atoms. This strategy leads us to use of the flexible ligands in contrast to the rigid organic spacers which are useful in the formation of open frameworks with different nodal geometries. As a result, we have used the flexible ligands viz. 1,2-bis (4-pyridyl) ethane (bpe); 1,3-bis (4-pyridyl) propane (bpp); 4,4‘-bipyridyl disulfide (bpds) to organize the metal centers into supramolecular arrays. Indeed, these extended aryl systems act as a self-recognition motif forming aryl−aryl interactions with another aryl system, and they are adequate to achieve directionally controlled aggregation in the solid state.

elements.content: Crystallographic Data Collection and Refinement. Suitable single crystals of complexes 2 and 3 were mounted on a Siemens SMART diffractometer equipped with a graphite monochromator and Mo Kα (λ = 0.71073 Å) radiation. The intensity data were corrected for Lorentz and polarization effects for all the complexes. The structures were solved by Direct method and followed by successive Fourier and difference Fourier syntheses. During refinement C6 → C12 atoms of the pendant bpp ligand in complex 2 were found to be disordered over two positions (C6 → C12 and C6a → C12a) with the occupancy ratio 0.6/0.4. The hydrogens on the solvent water molecule could not be located. In complex 3, all hydrogens on the guest water molecules were located by the difference Fourier method and were kept fixed. All other hydrogens in both the complexes were calculated geometrically. Full matrix least squares refinements on F 2 were carried out using SHELXL-97 with anisotropic displacement parameters for all non-hydrogen atoms for the complexes. All calculations were carried out using SHELXL 97, SHELXS 97, PLATON 99, ORTEP-32, and WinGX system, Ver 1.64. Data collection and structure refinement parameters and crystallographic data for complexes 2 and 3 are given in Table . The selected bond lengths, hydrogen-bonding interactions as well as the π−π interactions and C−H···π interactions parameters are summarized in Tables −6.

Crystal Structure of Complex 1. The X-ray structure has been reported earlier. X-ray crystallographic data reveal that complex 1 is a 1D sinusoidal chain (Figure a). The most interesting feature of 1 is the three-dimensional honeycomb-like molecular network, formed by the 1D chains in a cross-like fashion arrangement at the Mn(II) centers (Figure b). The planes of the bipyridyl rings are offset between the adjacent layers with a face-to-face separation with a center-to-center distance of 3.945(2) Å and dihedral angle of 8.130°. The offset of the barycenters separated by an interplanar distance of 3.600(2) Å indicates a π−π interaction, which is responsible for the formation of the honeycomb-like network. The network encapsulates a three-dimensional system of intersecting solvent-filled channels propagating along [100], [010] with hexagonal shape and along [001] with rhombic shape. elements.content: The chains of [Mn(bpp)3Cl2] n (Figure a) pack alongside each other to give a 2D sheet containing only π−π interactions (Figure b). One terminal pyridyl ring and one ligated pyridyl ring of bpp ligands of the two closest chains are linked through face-to-face π-interactions (perpendicular distance between centroids of the interacting rings, 4.095 Å; dihedral angle, 8.03°) and are responsible for the formation of the 2D architecture. Every such sheet is locked by a strong face-to-face π-interactions (Table ) passing through pendant pyridine ligands (perpendicular distance between centroids of the interacting rings, 3.401 Å; dihedral angle, 6.37°) to generate a 3D supramolecular architecture (Figure c), where the π−π interactions are mainly responsible for the formation of the solid-state structure. The 3D structure is further stabilized by C−H···π interactions with a <C−H···π angular range, 124.01−137.60° and C···π distance range, 3.634−3.753 Å (Table ). It is interesting to note that the latter π−π interactions form a pseudo square to facilitate a strong interaction and may be used as a synthon for directed syntheses of a structure.

elements.content: The packing diagram of 3 exhibits a 3D supramolecular architecture. First, the adjacent mononuclear entities are held together through hydrogen-bonding interactions between water molecules, (O1w, O2w), the free dicyanamide nitrogens (N5, N10) and the free pyridine nitrogens of bpds ligands, (N2, N7) to form the 2D sheet (Figure ). The introduction of water molecule in the coordination geometry facilitates the formation of the hydrogen bonds (Table ). When 2D networks are viewed in the [100] direction, it is revealed that these interactions lead to the formation of two types of chains along a side view. One chain contains channels with dimension ca. ∼7.4 × 7.4 Å17 with guest water molecules (Figure a) and the other with same dimension and structure but contains the solvent bpds molecules instead of water (Figure b). The topological chains are arranged alternately and linked each other through π−π interactions only (Table ). Also, the chains are arranged in an offset fashion to maximize the π−π interactions through ligated bpds molecules (Figure ). Further, the solvent bpds molecules are also engaged in strong π−π interactions. The perpendicular distance between centroids of the interacting rings is in the range, 3.416−3.803 Å and the range of the dihedral angle is 0°−13.19°. It is worthy to note that the special sandwiched π−π interactions may be used as synthon and the chains/sheets formed can be used in self-recognition of bpds. This 3D structure is further stabilized by C−H···π interactions with <C−H···π angle, 134.30° and C···π distance, 3.789 Å (Table ).

elements.content: Fluorescence Characterization. In the solid state, the fluorescence excitation spectra of all the three ligands (bpe, bpp, and bpds) show excitation bands at ∼220 nm (very strong) and ∼330 nm (weak). These two bands correspond well with the π−π* and n−π* transition for the pyridine chromophore. In methanol solvent, the same n−π* transition band gains good intensity and is slightly red shifted. This could be due to solvent stabilization. In the solid state, the ligand bpe shows two excitation bands at ∼220 nm (very strong) and ∼330 nm (weak) in the fluorescence excitation spectrum and both the excitation bands show a structured broad emission bands centered at ∼425 nm and at ∼610 nm. This emission is due to interligand charge-transfer transition.

elements.content: In the Mn(II)−bpe complex 1, the ∼220 nm excitation (π−π* excitation) band shows a fluorescence spectrum similar to that of the free ligand. On the other hand, the 330 nm excitation (n−π* excitation) does not show an emission band in the metal complex. This indicates that the lone-pair electrons (electrons in N atom) of the ligand (bpe) are involved in the formation of coordinate bonding to the Mn(II) ion. This fact corroborates the results obtained from the X-ray structure determination. In solid state, the pure ligand bpp shows a broad structure emission bands centered at ∼400 and ∼600 nm when excited at n−π* or π−π* excitation bands. This emission is due to interligand charge-transfer transition. In Mn(II)−bpp complex 2, the nature of the emission bands is similar to that of the ligand. Actually, if we take a look on the crystal structure of the complex 2, two types of bpp are present. One is bridging and another is pendant. In complex 2, one lone pair electron of pendant bpp is not involved in the formation of coordinate bonding to the metal ion. These free lone pair are responsible for the n−π* transition site in complex 2.

The same emission band appears as broad, structured, and slightly red shifted (λemission∼ 450 nm) in the emission spectrum of pure solid. It is found that this ∼450 nm fluorescence band of the ligand (bpds) in the solid state is quenched upon formation of complex 3 with Mn(II). The possible explanation is that the π-stacking interaction in the complex may lead to the formation of H-type aggregates and the allowed transition is to the top of the exciton band. In this case, fluorescence is essentially quenched and luminescence quantum yields are drastically decreased. There is no evidence of ligand-to-metal charge-transfer bands as was observed in other reported complexes.

The structural role of the linker on the bipyridyl thus appears to be entirely different in 1, 2, and 3. In 1, flexible bpe forms a honeycomb-like 3D framework by the π directed overlap of sinusoidal chains, whereas in 2 the more flexible bpp facilitates to lock the zigzag chains by only π-interactions forming a 2D standing wavelike topology. In complex 3, the self-recognition of bpds leads to the formation of very unprecedented sandwiched π−π interactions. In 1, there are two bisecting channels, whereas in 3 there are two types of alternating channels containing two types of guests.

Conclusions

We have showed three different building blocks containing Mn(II) and flexible bipyridyl ligand controlling the assembly mainly by weak and cooperative noncovalent interactions. The structural role of the linker on the bipyridyl thus appears to be entirely different in 1, 2, and 3. In 1, flexible bpe forms a honeycomb-like 3D framework by the π directed overlap of sinusoidal chains, whereas in 2 the more flexible bpp facilitates to lock the zigzag chains by only π-interactions forming a 2D standing wavelike topology. In complex 3, the self-recognition of bpds leads to the  formation of very unprecedented sandwiched π-π interactions. We have shown π-stacking forces are capable of forming self-assembly with channels in two cases. In 1, there are two bisecting channels, whereas in 3 there are two types of alternating channels containing two types of guests.
